  "prompt": "Why do some non-Asian Americans have an Asian last name like Lee, Li, Chang, Chung, etc.?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why non-Asian Americans might have an Asian last name:\n\n1. Historical immigration and assimilation\n- Adoption by Asian families\n- Marriage to an Asian spouse\n- Ancestors who immigrated from Asia\n\n2. Ethnic diversity\n- Mixed racial heritage\n- Multiracial or multicultural backgrounds\n\n3. Coincidental surname similarities\n- Some surnames like \"Lee\" can have different origins\n- Some names are common across different cultures\n- Not all people with these names have Asian ancestry\n\n4. Anglicization of names\n- Some surnames might have been modified over generations\n- Similar-sounding names from different cultural backgrounds\n\n5. Less common scenarios\n- Name changes\n- Formal name adoption\n- Personal choice\n\nWithout knowing a specific individual's background, it's impossible to pinpoint the exact reason for their last name.",
